    "back": "A discretionary trust imposes a duty on the trustee to distribute the property among the objects of the trust — the trustee must exercise the discretion (though they choose how). A mere power gives the holder (donee) a right but no obligation to appoint property — if the power is not exercised, the property goes to the default beneficiary. A fiduciary power (held by a trustee) requires the donee to periodically consider exercising the power, but they need not actually exercise it.",
