    "front": "What are the key equitable maxims and how do they guide the exercise of equitable jurisdiction?",
    "back": "Equitable maxims are guiding principles, not rigid rules: (1) Equity will not suffer a wrong without a remedy; (2) Equity follows the law (but is not bound by it); (3) He who comes to equity must come with clean hands; (4) Equity regards as done that which ought to be done (Walsh v Lonsdale); (5) Equity looks to intent, not form; (6) Where equities are equal, the first in time prevails; (7) Where equities are equal, the law prevails; (8) Equity acts in personam; (9) Delay defeats equity (laches).",
    "details": "These maxims express the values underlying equitable intervention: conscience, fairness, and the prevention of unconscionable conduct. 'Clean hands': a claimant who has acted unconscionably may be denied equitable relief (Dering v Earl of Winchelsea (1787)). 'Equity regards as done that which ought to be done': an agreement to grant a lease operates as a lease in equity (Walsh v Lonsdale). 'Equity acts in personam': equitable remedies are directed at the defendant personally — hence the court can order specific performance, injunctions, and account. Laches (delay): unreasonable delay in asserting equitable rights may bar a claim, even within the statutory limitation period.",
