    "back": "Dishonest assistance (Royal Brunei v Tan [1995]): a third party who dishonestly assists a trustee in a breach of trust is personally liable to account as if they were a trustee. The defendant need not have received trust property. Knowing (unconscionable) receipt (BCCI v Akindele [2001]): a third party who receives trust property (or its traceable substitute) for their own benefit, with a degree of knowledge that makes retention unconscionable, is personally liable to restore the value received.",
    "details": "Key differences: (1) assistance requires dishonesty (Ivey v Genting [2017] objective test) — receipt requires unconscionability (lower threshold debated); (2) assistance does not require receipt of trust property — receipt does; (3) both are personal claims (though proprietary tracing claims may run in parallel against a recipient). A third party who receives trust property as agent (not beneficially) is not liable under knowing receipt but may be liable under dishonest assistance if they helped the breach. The two claims are not mutually exclusive — a defendant who both receives and assists can face both.",
